metadata.description: {\rtf1\ansi\fs24{\fs48\b Geraint's JSFX repository\b}\line\line This is a collection of audio effects I have written in REAPER's JSFX language.\line\line Download them from GitHub <https://github.com/geraintluff/jsfx> or on ReaPack <https://reapack.com/> by adding the repository: https://geraintluff.github.io/jsfx/index.xml\line\line {\par \bullet\tab PadSynth - a synth that produces thick sounds, including per-note effects and modulators\line \bullet\tab Spring-Box - an echo/chorus effect\line \bullet\tab Bad Connection - flips between two volumes to simulate poor connection or dropouts\line \bullet\tab Sandwich Amp - distortion module with a before/after filter pair, width control and secondary input\line \bullet\tab Warble - a basic pitch-editing effect\line \bullet\tab Spectrum Matcher - analyse the difference between an input and a model, and optionally correct with EQ\line \bullet\tab Smooth Limiter - a limiter that aims to have the correction curve as smooth as possible\line \bullet\tab Panalysis - visualise and manipulate the stereo field of the audio\line }\linePresets (RPL) for these effects can be downloaded from GitHub.\line\line {\fs24\b PadSynth\b}\line\line This is a synth that specialises in smooth and thick sounds, with a bank of effects and assignable modulators that are calculated per-note. (audio demo <audio-demos/padsynth.mp3>, additional audio demos <https://soundcloud.com/geraintluff/sets/padsynth-demo-tracks-2/s-xUWj6>)\line\line You can find more information and demos for this synth on its main project page <https://github.com/geraintluff/jsfx-pad-synth>.\line\line (img)\line\line The per-note effects can re-ordered and renamed, and the modulators can modulate any later effect in the chain, including other modulators.\line\line (img)\line\line {\fs24\b Spring-Box\b}\line\line Spring-Box is a chorus/echo effect based on a matrix of 4 delay lines feeding back into each other. The delay lines vary in length according to the chorus parameters, so you can create a range of sounds from choruses and ambiences to space-like reverb effects. (audio demo <audio-demos/spring-box.mp3>)\line\line Early echoes can be suppressed to get a smoother sound (the "late bias" control), by using two parallel delay structures with different feedback ratios, and subtracting the results.\line\line (img)\line\line {\fs24\b Bad Connection\b}\line\line Bad Connection is an effect that randomly changes the audio between two volume levels. It can be used to imitate dodgy radios <audio-demos/Bad Connection/radio-dropout.mp3> or glitchy CPU overloads <audio-demos/Bad Connection/cpu-overload.mp3>.\line\line (img)\line\line {\fs24\b Sandwich Amp\b}\line\line Sandwich Amp is a distortion effect with a set of paired filters on either side, to provide a range of timbres. (audio demo <audio-demos/sandwich-amp.mp3>)\line\line The underlying distortion function is (inlinecode)tanh() (which is a fairly "soft" distortion, as opposed to a hard clip), but it can be driven quite hard, and an offset can be added to get asymmetrical response.\line\line The "width" parameter widens the sound before distortion and narrows it afterwards, so that the distortion sounds stable and central while preserving the stereo feel of the sound. Similarly, the "filter" section applies a filter before the distortion, and then applies the inverse filter afterwards, which can provide distinctive distortion timbres.\line\line It is also possible to supply a secondary input to the effect (channels 3 and 4) - this audio is added in before the distortion, but then subtracted again afterwards.\line\line (img)\line\line {\fs24\b Warble\b}\line\line Warble is a relatively basic pitch-editing plugin. It analyses incoming audio, stores and displays it on a zoomable graph (middle mouse and scroll wheel). (demo: original <audio-demos/warble-original.mp3>, minor correction <audio-demos/warble-subtle.mp3>, major alterations <audio-demos/warble-shifted.mp3>, formant LFO <audio-demos/warble-formant-mod.mp3>)\line\line There are three tools: nudge, erase and smooth. You use these tools with the mouse (left/right buttons do different things) to define how much it should be shifted. The current change amount is displayed in red.\line\line (img)\line\line The formant-correction on the shifting algorithm isn't perfect, so major corrections (e.g. 5 semitones or more) won't sound completely natural.\line\line It doesn't (currently) separate notes from each other, or support automatic correction. I haven't figured out how to make "undo" work properly, so that's something to look at in the future.\line\line {\fs24\b Spectrum Matcher\b}\line\line Spectrum Matcher is a tool for comparing the spectrum/timbre of an input against a model, and optionally applying a correction filter.\line\line The bottom half of the screen shows the short-term spectrum (green), the long-term spectrum (yellow), and the long-term reference spectrum (blue).\line\line The top half of the screen shows the current difference between the long-term spectrums (red). If correction is enabled, it shows the correction curve (white) and phase (dotted brown). If the correction is frozen, it shows the frozen correction values in blue.\line\line To disable correction and re-start/clear the long-term spectrum measurements, hit "Reset". To start correction, hit "Correct". Once correction is enabled, hit "Freeze" to set or update the fixed correction values.\line\line (img)\line\line It can learn new models from the incoming audio, and save this as a preset for later use:\line\line (img)\line\line This effect is quite CPU-intensive, so if you're not using it it could be good to bypass it.\line\line {\fs24\b Smooth Limiter\b}\line\line This is a brick-wall limiter that aims to keep the correction curve smooth while remaining responsive.\line\line It will recover completely from any peak in a fixed amount of time. Both the attack and release follow a curve that is similar to a sinusoidal segment ((inlinecode)1 + cos(x)), with the goal of reducing cross-modulation.\line\line (img)\line\line The "distortion" parameter changes the correction mode - at 0%, the correction is applied by scaling the output signal. At 100%, the correction is applied using a non-linear distortion (smooth, not a hard-clip), which can sound good for some applications such as drums. The display in the bottom-left shows the current correction response.\line\line {\fs24\b Panalysis\b}\line\line This effect draws the incoming audio on a 2D plot, so you can visualise the stereo field. You can also alter the width/pan using the controls.\line\line {\par \bullet\tab Centre-panned (mono) sounds will draw vertically\line \bullet\tab Left-panned sounds will draw angled to the left, right-panned will draw to the right\line \bullet\tab If the L+R channels are independent, the graph will have no defined clear direction (may appear round)\line }\line(img)\line\line It's possible to rotate the field such that hard-left or hard-right inputs will output "inside out" (opposite phase in both output channels). In this case, the Width dial will turn red - double-click the dial to reset it to the maximum "safe" width:\line\line (img)\line\line }
